`agents/` is the model-adapter boundary between `ctx-summarize`'s Rust core and whatever LLM actually generates summaries. Depending on this directory gets you one guarantee: invoke `$CTX_AGENT_CMD` via `sh -c`, feed it `{"system": <string>, "user": <string>}` JSON on stdin, and get back either raw completion text on stdout with exit 0, or nothing usable and a non-zero exit — no other error signal exists. Everything about model choice, prompting behavior, and provider quirks is isolated here so the Rust side never needs to change to swap providers.

The two files are spec and implementation of the same contract: README.md documents it, summarizer-claude.py is the reference adapter fulfilling it against Anthropic's Messages API. They must stay in sync — changing the stdin/stdout shape in one means updating the other. Both enforce the same non-obvious invariant: adapters are pure transport, adding no instructions of their own (prompt content lives in `prompts/summarizer-leaf.md` and `prompts/summarizer-rollup.md`), and both pin reasoning effort low / disable extended thinking as a deliberate cost/latency choice for this low-intelligence, strict-format workload — revisit only if task requirements change. Both scripts are intentionally outside the Rust lint regime.

A new provider adapter is a new sibling script honoring the same contract, not a modification to existing files or to Rust code; if adding one requires touching the Rust core, the decoupling has broken.